nodes.text: Unknown Speaker : Are those food shortages in supermarkets since 1st of January, teething problems with Brexit or are there are much deeper issues with the Irish sea boarder customs protocol
are those food shortages in supermarkets since 1st of January, teething problems with Brexit or are there are much deeper issues with the Irish sea boarder customs protocol
Arlene Foster : The protocol was brought in by Boris Johnson to try to get Brexit done
the protocol was brought in by Boris Johnson to try to get Brexit done

since the protocol came in, there have been difficulties with like steel

we voted against the withdrawal agreement

if it’s not a border then it is xxx

Michelle O'Neill : We can see the outworking of that and certainly from my assessment it is very clear that what we’re witnessing is a trade adjustment shock.

Michelle O'Neill : There have been tariffs on steel been imported into the north
Michelle O'Neill : My job as a political leader will be to uphold the protocol and ensure it is implemented in its entirety and to find answers to problems.
Fiona Bruce : You say a few weeks
Fiona Bruce : We are three weeks in it
we are three weeks after Brexit

Fiona Bruce : in terms of the protocol and the differences it has made, the prime minister said in December there’s no question of there being checks on goods going Northern Ireland to Great Britain or Great Britain to Northern Ireland

in terms of the protocol and the differences it has made, the prime minister said in December there’s no question of there being checks on goods going Northern Ireland to Great Britain or Great Britain to Northern Ireland

look at what the Brexit deal is, we’re part of the same customs territory

the goods are not checked

there is no question of there being checks on goods going from Great Britain to Northern Ireland

the point the UK government made was that Northern Ireland businesses will have unfettered access as part of the UK
